  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. In the United States, the Bank Secrecy Act and the USA PATRIOT Act are key legislative tools for combating money laundering. These laws require financial institutions to:\n\n1. Implement customer identification programs\n2. Report suspicious transactions\n3. Maintain detailed transaction records\n4. Conduct due diligence on customers\n5. Screen transactions against watchlists\n\nInternationally, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for AML regulations. Most developed countries have comprehensive legal frameworks to detect and prevent money laundering activities.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and potential imprisonment, depending on the jurisdiction and severity of the offense.",
